title: geth export does not work
body:
This is an re-opened issue, the original post is at https://github.com/ethereum/go-ethereum/issues/2749

```
    Geth
    Version: 1.4.5-stable-27df30f3

    Network Id: 1
    Go Version: go1.5.4
    OS: linux
```

```
    geth export dumps chain from datadir to filename
```

-------------------------------- Previous comments from karalabe --------------------------------

The logs state that your chain is empty:

```
    I0628 21:29:16.834694 core/blockchain.go:206] Last header: #0 [d4e56740…] TD=17179869184
    I0628 21:29:16.852534 core/blockchain.go:207] Last block: #0 [d4e56740…] TD=17179869184
    I0628 21:29:16.852608 core/blockchain.go:208] Fast block: #0 [d4e56740…] TD=17179869184
```

Hence why export can only export the genesis block. There doesn't seem to be anything else in there. Please check that you try to export from the correct data directory.

Closing as works as intended. Please reopen with more information if you believe there still is an issue and not just a slight user (datadir) error.

Please use `./geth  --datadir /mnt/vdb/hdchain/data export backup 0 100`. The datadir option follows `geth`, not the entire command. This should eventually be fixed but it's an oddity of a CLI package we used.

Thanks Karalade's suggestion, I finally got this work by specifying the --datadir option, and the 'geth export' cannot started when geth instance is running, I have to shutdown geth and then run 'geth export', this is not good for the production system, it's better to support **online expor**t.

On testnet, when i run export -testnet, even without specifying the datadir the export does succeed.

This worked for me:

```
geth export --datadir "directory" --syncmode "full" --cache 2048 backup.rlp fromBlockNumber toBlockNumber

rm directory/geth

geth --datadir "directory" init genesis.json

geth import backup.rlp --datadir "directory" --syncmode "full" --cache 2048
```

- directory : The directory where geth and key are located after Genesis is initialized
- fromBlockNumber: Backup will start from this block number
- toBlockNumber: Backup will be taken up this block

Example:

```
geth export --datadir "test" --syncmode "full" --cache 2048 backup.rlp 0 30100

rm test/geth

geth --datadir "test" init genesis.json

geth import backup.rlp --datadir "test" --syncmode "full" --cache 2048

```
